10226nam a22014895i 9783110220377DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20102011gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979588426  a97831102203777 a10.1515/97831102203772doi  a(DE-B1597)36888  a(OCoLC)710789589  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP281 7aLAN0090002bisacsh0481ua415.6qDE-101222/ger  aET 6552rvk0(DE-625)rvk/28013:00aStudies in Ditransitive Constructions :bA Comparative Handbook /ced. by Andrej Malchukov, Martin Haspelmath, Bernard Comrie. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2010] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (772 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis rich volume deals comprehensively with cross-linguistic variation in the morphosyntax of ditransitive constructions: constructions formed with verbs (like give) that take Agent, Theme and Recipient arguments. For the first time, a broadly cross-linguistic perspective is adopted. The present volume, consisting of an overview article and twenty-odd in-depth studies of ditransitive constructions in individual languages from different continents, arose from the conference on ditransitive constructions held at the Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology (Leipzig) in 2007. It opens with the editors' survey article providing an overview of cross-linguistic variation in ditransitive constructions, followed by the questionnaire on ditransitive constructions, compiled by the editors in order to elicit various properties of these patterns. The editors' overview discusses formal properties of ditransitive constructions as well as behavioral (or syntactic) and lexical properties (i.e., the extension of ditransitive constructions across different verb classes). The volume includes 23 contributions describing properties of ditransitive constructions in languages from all over the world, written by leading experts. Care has been taken that the contributions to the volume will be representative of structural, geographic and genealogical diversity in the domain of ditransitive constructions. Thus the present volume provides a unique source of information on typological diversity of ditransitive constructions. It is expected that it will be of central interest to all scholars and advanced students of linguistics, especially to those working in the field of language typology and comparative syntax.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aGenerative grammar. 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxTransitivity. 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxVerb. 0aSemantics. 4aDitransitives Verb. 4aFunktionale Grammatik. 4aSprachtypologie. 4aSyntax. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aFunctional Grammar.  aLanguage Typology.  aSyntax.1 aAtoyebi, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanjade, Goma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBassène, Alain-Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhatta, Toya N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBickel, Balthasar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoghill, Eleanor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aComrie, Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aComrie, Bernard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCreissels, Denis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrevels, Mily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v